05054nam a22009735i 9780674187757DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20131995mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013945817  a(OCoLC)1029819808  a(OCoLC)1032690461  a(OCoLC)1037981479  a(OCoLC)1042034735  a(OCoLC)1046605275  a(OCoLC)1047007523  a(OCoLC)1049633123  a(OCoLC)1054877828  a97806741877577 a10.4159/harvard.97806741877572doi  a(DE-B1597)250044  a(OCoLC)900809058  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aBUS0690002bisacsh1 aAckerman, Bruce, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIs NAFTA Constitutional? /cBruce Ackerman, David Golove.  aReprint 2014 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2013] 4c©1995  a1 online resource (129 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIS NAFTA CONSTITUTIONAL? -- tI. THE WORLD WE HAVE LOST -- tII. THE TWENTIES -- tIII. THE NEW DEAL ABROAD -- tIV. THE GREAT TRANSFORMATION -- tV. THE ERA OF CODIFICATION -- tVI. THE BIGGER PICTURE -- tVII. THE FUTURE DEBATE0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBy a vote of 61 to 38, the Senate joined the House in declaring that "Congress approves.the North American Free Trade Agreement." The vote was virtually unnoticed, since the real battle over NAFTA was in the House. But there is a puzzle here. The President, the Framers assure us, "shall have Power, by and with the Advice and Consent of the Senate, to make Treaties, provided two thirds of the Senators present concur." Whatever happened to the Treaty Clause? Bruce Ackerman and David Golove tell the story of the Treaty Clause's being displaced in the twentieth century by a modern procedure in which the House of Representatives joins the Senate in the process of consideration, but simple majorities in both Houses suffice to commit the nation. This is called the Congressional-Executive Agreement, and is a response to a sea change in public opinion during and after World War II. This agreement substituted for a failed constitutional amendment that would have required all treaties to be approved by majorities in both Houses rather than by two-thirds of the Senate. The modern Congressional-Executive Agreement was self-consciously developed in order to make formal constitutional amendment unnecessary. So, is NAFTA constitutional? This book is reprinted from the Harvard Law Review.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aFree trade. 0aHandel, Kommunikation, Verkehr. 0aInternational relations. 0aTreaty-making power. 0aVerfassungsmäßigkeit. 4aFree trade -- North America. 4aLAW / General. 4aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General. 4aTreaty-making power -- United States. 4aUnited States -- Foreign relations -- Executive agreements. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / General.2bisacsh1 aGolove, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488oZDB-23-HCO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Social Science eBook Packagez9783110353556oZDB-23-HCI08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z97831104422120 cprintz978067418774040uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067418775740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674187757423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674187757/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  